        <p>The childcare and school piece of single parenthood is largely a logistics problem — and logistics problems are solvable. What makes it hard is that the system wasn't designed with single parents in mind. Here's how to work it anyway.</p>

        <h2>Finding childcare</h2>
        <p>Your main options, from most to least expensive:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Daycare centers</strong> — licensed, structured, often the most reliable. Also the most expensive. Full-time infant care averages $1,000–2,000/month depending on location.</li>
          <li><strong>Family daycare (home-based)</strong> — smaller settings, often cheaper, quality varies more. Check your state's licensing requirements — licensed home daycares are inspected.</li>
          <li><strong>Nanny or au pair</strong> — expensive as a solo arrangement; much more affordable shared with another family ("nanny share"). Worth exploring if you have a neighbor in a similar situation.</li>
          <li><strong>Family</strong> — if grandparents or other family are willing and geographically close, this is often the most flexible and affordable option. Formalize the arrangement: agreed times, backup plan, what happens when the kid is sick.</li>
          <li><strong>Cooperative arrangements</strong> — swapping care with another single parent. You watch their kids Tuesday, they watch yours Thursday. Requires trust and similar schedules but costs nothing.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Childcare assistance</h3>
        <p>If cost is a barrier, federal childcare subsidies (CCAP/CCDF) may cover a significant portion. See the <a href="{{ '/financial/assistance/' | url }}">Assistance Programs guide</a> for details. Apply early — waitlists are common.</p>

        <h3>Finding providers</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><a href="https://childcare.gov/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">childcare.gov</a> — search licensed childcare providers in your area by zip code</li>
          <li>Your state's childcare licensing agency website — lists licensed home daycares and centers</li>
          <li>Ask at your child's pediatrician office — they hear recommendations constantly</li>
        </ul>

