        <h2>After-school care</h2>
        <p>The gap between school ending (2:30–3pm) and work ending (5–6pm) is one of the hardest logistical problems for single parents. Options:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>School-based programs</strong> — many schools offer before/after care on-site. Often subsidized and the most convenient option. Ask your school office.</li>
          <li><strong>YMCA / Boys &amp; Girls Club</strong> — after-school programs with transportation from many schools. Income-based sliding scale pricing. <a href="https://www.ymca.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ymca.org</a> and <a href="https://www.bgca.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">bgca.org</a></li>
          <li><strong>Activity-based programs</strong> — sports leagues, arts programs, and similar activities cover several afternoons per week and overlap with childcare.</li>
          <li><strong>Homework clubs and tutoring programs</strong> — local libraries and community centers often run free after-school programs.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Communicating with schools</h2>
        <p>Schools often default to notifying mothers. Getting yourself in the system as an active, informed parent matters — both for your kids and for how the school perceives your family.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Make sure your contact information is current in the school's records</strong> — your email, your phone, and ideally a note that you are the primary or co-primary caregiver.</li>
          <li><strong>Request to be on all school communications</strong> — newsletters, grade reports, teacher communications. Many school systems now use apps (ClassDojo, Seesaw, ParentSquare) that allow both parents to be connected.</li>
          <li><strong>Introduce yourself to your child's teacher at the start of the year.</strong> A quick email or a minute at drop-off goes a long way. Teachers who know you respond differently when something comes up.</li>
          <li><strong>Be specific about custody arrangements when relevant.</strong> Schools need to know who can pick up your child. If pickups change week to week, give the office a calendar or a standing note.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Navigating custody schedules and school</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Get a copy of the school calendar early</strong> and map it against your custody schedule. Flag conflicts — holidays that fall on the other parent's days, field trips, conferences — before they become last-minute issues.</li>
          <li><strong>Keep a school bag packed and ready</strong> that doesn't need to transfer between homes. Duplicating the essentials (lunch bag, library books, gym shoes) at each home reduces handoff friction significantly.</li>
          <li><strong>Parent-teacher conferences:</strong> both parents can attend, even if you go separately. Request two time slots or ask if the teacher will do a brief separate call.</li>
          <li><strong>School forms</strong> often list only one emergency contact. Add yourself and make sure you're listed as a parent, not just an emergency contact.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Summer and school breaks</h2>
        <p>Summer is a four-month childcare problem for working single parents. Plan early:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Summer camps</strong> — day camps fill up by February in many areas. Many offer sliding-scale or scholarship options if cost is a concern. Ask about financial aid when you register.</li>
          <li><strong>YMCA summer programs</strong> — full-day summer programs available in most areas, often at lower cost than private camps.</li>
          <li><strong>Parks and recreation</strong> — most cities run affordable summer programs through their parks department. Under-marketed and often overlooked.</li>
          <li><strong>Library programs</strong> — free summer reading programs with activities, typically half-day. Doesn't cover full days but fills gaps.</li>
          <li><strong>Family</strong> — if grandparents or relatives can take stretches of summer, coordinate that early and map it to your work schedule.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout">
          <p><strong>Build a backup network.</strong> Every single parent needs a short list of people who can help in a pinch — a sick kid day, a late meeting, a schedule collision. Two or three trusted people willing to be called on occasionally is worth more than any individual childcare arrangement. Offer the same in return when you can.</p>
        </div>
